To reference the value of a field or menu item, use the variable name and the FIELD() function. For example:
title = 'Destry Rides Again';
FIELD(title).Value;

You can reference the object represented by a field or menu item instead of its value, using the FIELD() function.
For example, the following statement changes the background color of an entry field:
FIELD(title).BgColor = CC_ORANGE;

You can define your own default value for a variable by specifying this value in the variable declaration statement, as 
described in Variable Declaration. The syntax is similar to declaring a new class:
i = integer not null default 3;

Yes, when you create an entry field or a menu item, you can set the initial value for that field or menu item. 
For example, assuming that you have created a menu item and entered the variable name as *title*, you can set the 
value in that menu item with the following statement: title = 'Destry Rides Again';

In OpenROAD Actian 4GL, a variable that holds a reference to an object is called a reference variable. The value of a 
reference variable is not the object itself, but rather the memory address of the object in the heap. For example, if 
you define a class with attributes x and y, you can declare variables ix and iy as follows:
```
class C
{
   integer x;
   integer y;
};
```
Here, ix and iy are reference variables that hold the memory addresses of the object. These references can be used 
within their scope to access members of the class. However, they cannot be used outside of their scope, such as when you 
try to pass them to a subroutine or use them in an expression. When you declare a variable that is not a reference, 
OpenROAD allocates memory for it and copies the value into the variable. The variable can then be used anywhere in the 
application, such as in expressions, subroutines, or methods of other classes.

The initialize statement is used to declare variables and assign them a value when the frame or application starts. 
For example, the following code sets a variable of integer type, not null, with its default value 3: i = integer not 
null default 3;
